---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';

// Pull every experiment, drop drafts, newest entry first.
const all = (await getCollection('experiments')).filter((e) => !e.data.draft);
all.sort((a, b) => b.data.entry - a.data.entry);

// The "Oneirogens tested" figure is derived from the collection length.
const matrix = [
  { entry: 1, substance: 'Silene Capensis', sci: 'Silene Capensis', tradition: 'Ubulawu / Zulu / Xhosa', lucidity: '', dose: '', prep: '', tags: '' },
  { entry: 2, substance: 'Mexican Dream Herb', sci: 'Calea zacatechichi', tradition: 'Chontal', lucidity: 'Y', dose: '', prep: '', tags: '' },
  { entry: 3, substance: 'Synaptolepis kirkii', sci: 'Synaptolepis kirkii', tradition: 'Ubulawu / Zulu / Xhosa', lucidity: '', dose: '', prep: '', tags: '' },
  { entry: 4, substance: 'Mugwort', sci: 'Artemisia vulgaris', tradition: '', lucidity: 'Y', dose: '2g', prep: 'tea, pre-bed', tags: '' },
  { entry: 5, substance: 'Galantamine', sci: '', tradition: 'Western Medicine', lucidity: 'Y', dose: '8mg', prep: 'WBTB', tags: 'cholinergic' },
  { entry: 6, substance: 'Huperzine A', sci: '', tradition: 'Eastern Medicine', lucidity: '', dose: '200 and 400mcg', prep: 'WBTB', tags: 'cholinergic' },
  { entry: 7, substance: 'Blue Lotus', sci: 'Nymphaea caerulea', tradition: 'Egyptian', lucidity: '', dose: '5g', prep: 'tea, pre-bed, WBTB', tags: '' },
  { entry: 8, substance: 'African Fever Tree', sci: '', tradition: 'Ubulawu / Zulu / Xhosa', lucidity: '', dose: '2g', prep: 'tea, pre-bed, WBTB', tags: '' },
];

const count = matrix.length;

const pad = (n: number) => String(n).padStart(3, '0');
const score = (n: number | null) => (n === null || n === undefined ? '—' : `${n}/5`);
---
<Base active="home">

  <!-- HERO -->
  <div class="hero">
    <div class="wrap">
      <img class="mk-big" src="/assets/nightcone_square_icon.png" alt="Nightcone Labs" style="mix-blend-mode:multiply" />
      <h1>A field observatory for the dreaming mind.</h1>
      <p class="lede">Nightcone Labs runs structured, single-variable experiments on oneirogens, which are compounds reported to alter dreams and dream content. We publish what actually changes, including the nights that nothing does.</p>
      <div class="cta-row">
        <a class="btn solid" href="#matrix">See the matrix</a>
        <a class="btn ghost" href="#experiments">See the experiments</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- STAT -->
  <section style="padding-top:0">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="stats stats-single">
        <a class="cell" href="#matrix" style="text-decoration:none;color:inherit;cursor:pointer"><div class="num">{count}</div><div class="lab">Oneirogens tested</div></a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ABOUT -->
  <section id="about">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="eyebrow">The project</p>
      <h2>A field observatory for the distinctly human experience of dreaming.</h2>
      <p>Dreaming is one of the last common human experiences that remains poorly instrumented. We sleep, dream, and most of it is gone by breakfast. A long list of historical and ethnobotanical traditions claim that certain plants and compounds, referred to as oneirogens, can change that: sharpen recall, intensify the imagery, or tip a sleeper into lucidity. The clinical literature, by contrast, is thin. There are a handful of controlled trials at sleep labs, a great deal of folk anecdotes, and essentially no clean answers.</p>
      <p>Nightcone exists to fill that gap. The premise is simple and deliberately methodical: take one compound at a time, hold the protocol fixed, run it for long enough to separate signal from a noisy baseline, and record the result whether or not it&apos;s interesting. The methodology is shared. Tests are sourced from traditions such as dream practice or divination cultures that named these plants. The results are intended to speak to biohackers, sleep enthusiasts, and the dream curious.</p>
      <p>The output is a growing record: a matrix of compounds, doses, protocols, and outcomes that compounds over time into an encyclopedia of dream modification. The future state goal is for the user to be able to choose a desired dream result, and be able to understand what chemistry is needed to achieve that goal.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PRINCIPLES -->
  <section id="principles">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="eyebrow">How the work is run</p>
      <h2>Method before narrative.</h2>
      <div class="grid2" style="margin-top:34px">
        <div class="principle">
          <h3>One variable at a time</h3>
          <p>Every oneirogen is tested on its own on a chemical basis. Tests include no stacking, no behavioral techniques layered in, and no dream journaling unless it's the thing being tested. The point is to isolate the chemical impact first. If an effect appears, it should be attributable to one input.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="principle">
          <h3>The 7-night standard</h3>
          <p>Protocols run for at least seven consecutive nights at a fixed dose and fixed timing, with a washout when relevant. Dreams vary wildly night to night, so a single trial proves almost nothing. Some compounds have build-up effects versus acute ones, so an extended protocol helps capture these subtle signals.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="principle">
          <h3>Null results are results</h3>
          <p>Most things in this category, tested skeptically, don't do much. Compounds that produce nothing get the same write-up as the ones that work. A documented null effect saves an identical multi-night test.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="principle">
          <h3>Mechanism stays hypothesis-level</h3>
          <p>Where a pathway is plausible, such as cholinergic compounds and REM, it's stated with its level of validation. We are not inventing mechanisms, and don't promise outcomes the evidence can't support.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- MATRIX (generated from experiments) -->
  <section id="matrix">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="eyebrow">The matrix</p>
      <h2>The central, cumulative artifact.</h2>
      <p class="muted" style="max-width:62ch">Every compound tested is a row: substance, scientific name, cultural tradition, dose, preparation, and whether it produced a lucid dream. The matrix is the central, cumulative artifact; individual videos are just how each row gets reported.</p>
      <div class="matrix-shell" style="margin-top:26px">
        <table class="matrix">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Entry</th><th>Substance</th><th>Scientific name</th><th>Cultural tradition</th><th>Lucidity?</th><th>Dose</th><th>Preparation</th><th>Tags</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {matrix.map((e) => (
              <tr>
                <td class="ent">{pad(e.entry)}</td>
                <td>{e.substance}</td>
                <td>{e.sci || '—'}</td>
                <td>{e.tradition || '—'}</td>
                <td>{e.lucidity || '—'}</td>
                <td>{e.dose || '—'}</td>
                <td>{e.prep || '—'}</td>
                <td>{e.tags || '—'}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="matrix-cap">Lucidity (Y) marks runs where a lucid dream occurred. The matrix grows with every entry.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- EXPERIMENTS (generated from experiments) -->
  <section id="experiments">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="eyebrow">Experiments in detail</p>
      <h2>What's been tested, and what it suggested.</h2>
      <div style="margin-top:30px">
        {all.map((e) => (
          <div class="exp">
            <div class="exp-head">
              <h3><a href={`/experiments/${e.id}/`}>{e.data.title}</a></h3>
              {e.data.meta && <span class="meta">{e.data.meta}</span>}
            </div>
            <p>{e.data.summary}</p>
            {e.data.tags.map((t, i) => (
              <span class={'tag' + (e.data.nullResult && i === 0 ? ' null' : '')}>{t.replace(/-/g, ' ')}</span>
            ))}
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
      <p class="muted" style="margin-top:24px">Full write-ups and the running video record live on the <a href="https://www.youtube.com/@nightcone_labs" target="_blank" rel="noopener">YouTube</a> and <a href="https://www.tiktok.com/@nightcone_labs" target="_blank" rel="noopener">TikTok</a> channels. Each clip is one matrix row, reported as data.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- COMMITMENTS -->
  <section id="commitments">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="eyebrow">Where we stand</p>
      <h2>Commitments &amp; what's ruled out.</h2>
      <div class="grid2" style="margin-top:30px">
        <div>
          <h3>We commit to</h3>
          <p class="muted">Publishing null and ambiguous findings transparently. Mechanism-forward framing over dosage-forward. Treating the matrix as a compounding public artifact. Restraint as a stance, not an afterthought.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3>Ruled out</h3>
          <p class="muted">Mysticism and wellness softness. Hype marketing and guaranteed outcomes. Stacking recommendations. Anything sold as a cure. This is a record, not a product.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="muted" style="margin-top:30px;font-size:15px"><strong>Not medical advice.</strong> Nightcone documents self-experimentation for research interest. Compounds discussed can carry real toxicity and interaction risks. Nothing here is a recommendation to ingest anything.</p>
      <div class="cta-row" style="justify-content:flex-start;margin-top:30px">
        <a class="btn solid" href="/journal/">Read the journal</a>
        <a class="btn ghost" href="/faq/">Read the FAQ</a>
        <a class="btn ghost" href="/contact/">Get in touch</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</Base>
